sessions.title: Bringing Software Engineering Rigour to Data
sessions.description:
As a consultant with a software background, I get to see a lot of gaps in the data engineering world. The gap of maturity between the data and software communities in engineering rigour is the most prominent one.  

In software engineering, we have learnt that building robust and stable applications has a direct correlation with overall organisation performance as outlined in the industry leading Accelerate State of DevOps research by DevOps Research and Assessment (DORA). This is achieved through practices like infrastructure-as-code for deployments, automated testing, application observability, and end-to-end application lifecycle ownership. 

Although the data community is scratching the surfaces of possibility and striving to incorporate the core concepts, it is far from reaching its full potential.

In this talk, I will go through ways to leverage software engineering good practices into data engineering and demonstrate how measuring key performance metrics could help build more robust and reliable data pipelines.

sessions.title: Data Poker not Data Chess - thinking in Bets for Data Teams
sessions.description:
Data science and machine learning are deep into their business hype cycle - in 2023, every CEO wants to be “data-driven” in their strategy. As data practitioners, we are regularly relied upon to contribute to key strategic decisions:

- Will this dataset support an ML use-case we think our customers want?
- Do we need a streaming architecture? 
- Should we self-host Spark, or go with a vendor-managed service?
- Is it worth uplifting our simple ML model to use a shiny deep learning technique?
- When should we embed our data analysts and scientists in cross functional teams vs locating them in an enabling team that provides org-wide support?
- Are there even times it just isn’t appropriate to apply data science thinking?

Get enough of these decisions right, and you will be on the road to enabling your teams to build high-performing data products, and share valuable insights across your organisation. Get them wrong, and you will start to see a pattern of data-dependent projects under-delivering, gain a reputation for spending like drunken (data) sailors, experience runaway total cost-of-ownership, and face ongoing challenges unlocking the value of your organisation’s data. 

In this talk we will attempt to persuade you that all strategic decisions (including those made by data practitioners) should be thought of as bets, and that decision quality should not be evaluated by outcomes alone, as outcomes of past decisions are determined by a combination of skill & luck. 

We need to cultivate the ability to differentiate between skill and luck, so that we can make appropriately sized bets that are proportionate with our degree of uncertainty, and so we can push the right feedback from decision outcomes into our learning loops.

The DIBBs Framework, popularised by Spotify (based on work by Annie Duke) is a structured process for decomposing strategic decisions into Data, Insight, then Belief, to support appropriately sized Bets. This talk will take you through the framework, and show you ways in which you can use it to make better decisions both within your data teams and at the broader data strategy level of your organisation. A structured approach like DIBBs, acknowledging luck and uncertainty, will likely improve progress towards an organisational North Star over time.

sessions.title: Metadata driven framework for data discovery and data quality
sessions.description:
In this session, we will present a metadata driven rule based framework that allows us to capture and classify the policies/checks, translate them into executable rules and incorporates a weighted scoring model for reporting and analytics purposes. 
The main points of this session would be:  
1. The foundation framework.
2. How it integrates with any tools/technologies with open API architecture.
3. The tools/tech stack we used - Amundsen (data discovery) and Anomalo (data quality)

sessions.title: Shifting Data Left
sessions.description:
With several engineering teams building components autonomously, Kafka was selected as the single platform for cross-domain business event communication.

While one problem was solved, i.e. real-time access to events, quite quickly many more challenges arose as the complexity grew - and a plan was hatched to bring analytical Data Products as a 1st class concern of the engineering teams.

This talk outlines the early stage and WIP journey of a greenfields product build at a large enterprise, building a new digital business.

sessions.title: Designing Data Governance Framework
sessions.description:
Data Governance is an emerging trend in enterprise information management. This is mainly because organizations are becoming increasingly serious about the notion of "data as a strategic asset" as they face increasing pressure for reporting a "single source of the truth." 

Also, pursuant to legislative compliance mandates such as the Sarbanes-Oxley (SOX) Act and Basel II, Data Governance has recently gained significant prominence in practitioners' conferences, such as TDWI (The Data Warehousing Institute) World Conference and DAMA (Data Management Association) International Symposium. Research has evidenced the need for Data Governance in organisations to manage data effectively. It is only by effective data management that organisations can ensure good quality data which can be measured by its accuracy, timeliness, relevance, completeness, trustworthiness and contextual definition. 

However, studies have also revealed that large organisation that
has adopted an ad-hoc Data Governance model to manage its data found that its data management efforts were hampered by the lack of clear roles and responsibilities and the lack of mandate to carry out data quality improvement initiatives. 

The objective of this paper is to provide an overall framework for data governance that can be used by organisations to develop an effective data governance approach, strategy and design.

sessions.title: Data Security for Data Engineers
sessions.description:
Everybody forgets data engineers are in the thick of it. They are handling, transforming piping the data into something or somewhere.
Since attending a cybersecurity bootcamp over the past almost 6 months, (no I'm not all of a sudden a security expert), but with increased awareness of the vulnerabilities exploited, I have been talking to data architects/engineers about their current security practices and how they contribute to or implement data security… e.g leveraging their CI/CD pipelines to include security tests etc, vetting packages/dependencies etc

sessions.title: Well-Architecture Framework for Machine Learning
sessions.description:
Well Architecture Framework is considered to be more suited to well-set Solution Patterns. Whilst Machine Learning could have many moving parts, join me in understanding how you can leverage WAF principles with ML Workloads in Cloud. 

We will start with typical moving parts in (any) ML Project, and then will see the solution from WAF lens.

sessions.title: Data Manifold - Simplified Data Management on AWS
sessions.description:
A new open source solution from AWS, simplified data management and analytics experience using AWS native services.

Analysts can combine multiple disparate source of data and produce insights from external analytics systems with ease, without the need for custom development. Data Manifold is easily deployed within a customer’s AWS account as a CloudFormation template, reducing the effort needed to build a traditional data lake or purchase costly proprietary software.

Through an intuitive interface, users can seamlessly ingest, transform, govern, and query diverse data sources using familiar SQL syntax.

sessions.title: Customer Journey Analytics using Neo4j Graph Platform
sessions.description:
Today we live in a highly connected world where customers have several touchpoints to interact with the service or product providers. Customer journey represents every customer engagement with a service or product provider. Enabling the customer journey puts the organisation directly in the consumer's mind, so they can see and understand their customer's lifecycle, needs, and perceptions.

In this session, we aim to show customer journey in action and:
1. Introduce Neo4j and the concept of graph
2. Model, structure and represent customer journey in Neo4j
3. Visualise and influence customers' journeys using a trigger event model

sessions.title: Best of Stream + Batch: When Streaming Analytics Isn’t
sessions.description:
As data streams have moved from a niche technology to the new normal, the need to analyze streams has become ever-greater. Many stream processors, led by Apache Spark™, and simple stream analyzers, such as ksql for Kafka and Amazon Kinesis Analytics, claim to fill this gap. But they are missing key functions to provide useful real-time analytics. 

Gian Merlino, Apache Druid® committer and co-founder of Imply will show how real-time analytics combines stream and batch data at scale, with low latency, high concurrency, and reliable resilience. See how real-time analytics enables the best of stream + batch.

sessions.title: Data Privacy Engineering to power Responsible Enterprise AI
sessions.description:
Have you ever wondered how to protect customer data privacy when enabling large-scale AI systems. What if the insights generated by AI could be used to re-identify your customers. This is where data privacy engineering comes in. 
This talk will give an overview of different technologies including Data Clean Rooms, Homomorphic Encryption, Differential Privacy and AI Fairness which help enable responsible enterprise AI, while sharing data & insights within and outside organisational boundaries.

sessions.title: Building a Scalable, Reproducible Ontology System to Improve Deep Learning Data
sessions.description:
Artificial Intelligence (AI) requires large amounts of labelled training data for models to be accurately trained. In semantic segmentation, each pixel is assigned a value based on which class or classes it belongs to. On the other hand, an ontology is a collection of classes, their properties and the relationships between them. Semantic segmentation, then, lends itself quite naturally to integration with an ontology, where insights from the direct and indirect relationships between classes can be used to enhance the training data.

Recently, Nearmap has introduced an ontology system, which integrates directly into our labelling software, linking labelled data directly to the definitions in the ontology. Preliminary work on the system has already helped identify conflicts between labels in the production dataset.

Along the way, a number of challenges unique to managing Nearmap’s large geospatial dataset had to be overcome. We present our solution which handles reproducibility, version tracking, multiple perspectives in the source imagery and the storage of image examples as part of the class definitions.

sessions.title: Engineering Trust in Data
sessions.description:
Is building trust a technical problem? How will an organisation know when data is trusted? Who is the arbiter of trust, and how do they communicate their confidence in the data? These are some of the many questions that inevitably arise when organisations move from data strategies to data operations. 

Unfortunately, most organisations are simply not in a position to know that the market has consistently overcomplicated the technical delivery of data solutions whilst simultaneously underserving the complex and ever-evolving needs of business teams. This dichotomy effectively undermines organisational trust in data and dooms the vast majority of data initiatives to failure.  By contrast, an organisation that starts small and moves quickly, matches investment and technology to value delivered, and continuously improves upon its capabilities builds confidence in data and accelerates the time-to-value of data solutions.

In this talk a rigorous, engineering-led methodology for building trust in data will be presented. Key components of a continuous improvement framework for data solutions will be shared and tools for implementing them will be discussed. These frameworks and methodologies leverage lessons gathered over the course of 15 years of delivering data solutions in Australia and will be supported by three real-world case studies that have delivered billions of dollars in combined value back to their organisations.

sessions.title: Data replication patterns 101
sessions.description:
At the core of data engineering is the need to move data from one source to another. To do this successfully there are multiple architectural decisions a data engineer has to make: Batch, micro batch or streaming? What data storage to use? How to solve for idempotency? It can be difficult to navigate these decisions without understanding the relationship and dependencies between data use cases, replication patterns and supporting data infrastructure.

In this talk we will outline some common data replication patterns and their associated use cases. We will describe the constraints of each of the patterns, break them down into their core components and describe how to apply them to real world problems. We will share principles you can apply when choosing data infrastructure and detail what to consider when solving for idempotency.

sessions.title: Data Engineering simplified with Snowpark for Python on Snowflake
sessions.description:
Snowpark brings deeply integrated, DataFrame-style programming to the languages developers like to use – as well as functions to help them expand more data use cases easily. It enables data engineers, data scientists, and developers coding in languages like Python to take advantage of Snowflake’s powerful platform without having to first move data out of Snowflake.

During this hands-on session, you’ll learn:

- Setting up your favorite IDE (e.g. Jupyter, VSCode) for Snowpark
- Analyzing data and performing data engineering tasks using Snowpark DataFrames
- Using open-source Python libraries with near-zero maintenance or overhead
- Deploying ML model training code to Snowflake using Python Stored Procedures
- Creating and registering Python User-Defined Functions (UDFs) for inference

sessions.title: What is the MVP for Data Engineering projects?
sessions.description: The Minimum Viable Product is a central technique in software development to get products out asap for feedback. How do we do this for Data Engineering initiatives, which often involve complex pipelines spanning multiple teams? This lightning talk is a cautionary tale based on two large Data Engineering projects I’ve been on at different companies where I failed to establish fast feedback cycles. I will present some ideas on how we can do agile Data Engineering and would love to hear yours.

sessions.title: Delta Lake: Turn your Data Lake into a Lakehouse
sessions.description:
With Databricks open-sourcing all of Delta Lake in July, now is a great time to explore how open source Delta Lake enables a Lakehouse. In this session we'll look at how Delta Lake brings data warehouse capabilities (e.g. ACID guarantees, fast SQL execution, governance controls, etc.) to your data lake; and best practices for managing a secure, performant, and cost-effective Lakehouse

In this session we will use live examples to deep-dive on:
- What Delta Lake is doing under the hood
- Deconstructing Delta Lake's transaction logs
- Getting the best out of Delta Lake
-- Optimise file-skipping with OPTIMIZE, ZORDER, and VACUUM
-- Time travel semantics
-- DEEP & SHALLOW CLONEs
-- Tuning stats
-- CDC with Change Data Feeds (CDFs)

Q&A

sessions.title: Data Engineering for Social Good
sessions.description: It is no secret that data driven decision making can significantly increase the effectiveness of charities. However, the non-profit sector is often left behind in the pursuit of data insights due to lack of resources, time and know-how. This session will explore some of the unique challenges that non-profits face when establishing a data capability, and how simple solutions can create impact and drive social good.

sessions.title: AI as an API
sessions.description:
Train a ML Model and turn it into a REST API using Jupyter, TensorFlow, DataStax Astra DB and FastAPI.

In this talk we apply Machine Learning to the problem of Spam filtering. We will create a deep learning model from multiple spam datasets and make that available as an API. The talk is broken down into the following stages:
- Combining 2 open source spam datasets curated by The University of California, Irvine (UCI).
- Preparing a new dataset to be fully ready for training a model. 
- Building and training an LSTM model leveraging Keras.
- Creating an API to expose the model for use leveraging FastAPI
- Storing inference data for improving future predictions

sessions.title: Data Incidents - When things goes wrong
sessions.description:
After you build all your alarms, your test coverage is in place, observability tools running. Things can still goes wrong. So how to deal with Data Incidents?

Incidents are a huge part of the daily work of any software engineering team, but when it reach the data teams where we have, data analysts, analytics engineers and data scientists. How to identify an incident, how to communicate and how to ensure continuous improvement? This talk will share the experience of SafetyCulture dealing with Incidents in the Data Analytics Team.

sessions.title: Change the way you write. Change the way you think.
sessions.description:
Many data engineering problems stem from not being able to see the real problem from the correct angle. In fact the burgeoning industry of data engineering stems from our inability to tackle things at the simplest form. 

In this talk, I show a different way to think about problems and how it would lead to simplified data engineering processes everywhere.

This of course, isn't new. The games industry frequently use the same technique I will introduce in this talk to solve problems. 

By the end of this talk, I hope that you will join me in chanting: 
 DEATH TO YAML
